Lecture-34
Significance Levels and P values

1. The Big Picture

Hypothesis testing helps us decide whether the data provides enough evidence to reject a ‚Äúno effect‚Äù or ‚Äústatus quo‚Äù claim (the null hypothesis, H‚ÇÄ).
To make that decision, we calculate:

A test statistic ‚Äî derived from our sample data

A P-value ‚Äî how extreme that statistic is if H‚ÇÄ were true

A significance level (Œ±) ‚Äî our predefined cutoff for what counts as ‚Äútoo extreme‚Äù

2. Significance Level (Œ±)

Definition: The significance level represents the threshold for rejecting the null hypothesis.
It is the probability of making a Type I error, meaning rejecting H‚ÇÄ when it is actually true.

Common values:

Œ± = 0.10 ‚Üí more tolerant of false positives

Œ± = 0.05 ‚Üí standard level used in most studies

Œ± = 0.01 or 0.001 ‚Üí very strict, used in critical applications such as medicine

Interpretation:
If Œ± = 0.05, we are willing to accept a 5% chance of incorrectly concluding that there is an effect when there actually isn‚Äôt.

3. P-Value (Probability Value)

Definition:
The P-value is the probability of obtaining a test statistic as extreme or more extreme than what was observed, assuming the null hypothesis is true.

Mathematically:

ùëÉ=ùëÉ(data as or more extreme than observed‚à£ùêª0 true)
P=P(data as or more extreme than observed‚à£H0 true)

Interpretation:

Small P ‚Üí data is unlikely under H‚ÇÄ ‚Üí reject H‚ÇÄ

Large P ‚Üí data is plausible under H‚ÇÄ ‚Üí fail to reject H‚ÇÄ

Decision rule:

If P ‚â§ Œ±, reject the null hypothesis.

If P > Œ±, fail to reject the null hypothesis.

4. Coin Toss Example

Setup:

Null hypothesis (H‚ÇÄ): The coin is fair ‚Üí P(Heads) = 0.5

Alternative (H‚ÇÅ): The coin is biased toward tails ‚Üí P(Heads) < 0.5

Observed: 3 heads in 10 flips

Step 1: Choose significance level
Œ± = 0.05

Step 2: Compute the P-value
Under H‚ÇÄ (a fair coin), the number of heads follows a binomial distribution:

ùëã‚àºBinomial(ùëõ=10,ùëù=0.5)
X‚àºBinomial(n=10,p=0.5)

We calculate:

ùëÉ(ùëã‚â§3)=0.171
P(X‚â§3)=0.171

This means there is a 17.1% chance of observing 3 or fewer heads in 10 flips if the coin is fair.

Step 3: Compare with Œ±
Since 0.171 > 0.05, we fail to reject H‚ÇÄ.
The data is not extreme enough to conclude that the coin is unfair.

5. Business Applications
Scenario	Null Hypothesis (H‚ÇÄ)	Alternative (H‚ÇÅ)	Appropriate Œ±	Reasoning
Marketing Campaign	The campaign has no effect on sales	The campaign increases sales	0.10	Less harm in a false positive
Medical Drug Test	The drug has no effect	The drug helps recovery	0.001	Critical to avoid false positives
Website Layout A/B Test	The layout change has no impact	The layout change affects traffic	0.05	Balanced approach
6. Relationship Between Significance Level, Power, and Sample Size

Lower Œ± reduces the chance of a Type I error but increases the chance of a Type II error (failing to detect a real effect).

Larger sample sizes increase the power of the test, meaning a higher probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis.

Choosing Œ± should balance the seriousness of errors and the practical context of the decision.
